Here are both approaches for MAUI Shell navigation with `IQueryAttributable`:

**1. Navigate with a string parameter (product ID):**

```csharp
// From ProductListPage (or its ViewModel)
await Shell.Current.GoToAsync($"{nameof(ProductDetailsPage)}?productId={product.Id}");
```

**2. Navigate with a full object:**

```csharp
var navParams = new Dictionary<string, object>
{
    { "product", selectedProduct }   // complex object
};
await Shell.Current.GoToAsync(nameof(ProductDetailsPage), navParams);
```

**3. Receive both on the target ViewModel with `IQueryAttributable`:**

```csharp
public class ProductDetailsViewModel : ObservableObject, IQueryAttributable
{
    public void ApplyQueryAttributes(IDictionary<string, object> query)
    {
        // Approach 1 – simple string
        if (query.TryGetValue("productId", out var idObj))
        {
            string productId = idObj.ToString();
            // Load product from a service using productId
        }

        // Approach 2 – full object
        if (query.TryGetValue("product", out var obj) && obj is Product product)
        {
            // Use product directly
        }
    }
}
```

**Key differences:**

| | String param | Object param |
|---|---|---|
| **Navigation call** | URI query string | `Dictionary<string, object>` overload |
| **Survives serialization** | Yes (URL-safe) | No (in-memory only) |
| **Best for** | Deep links, simple IDs | Avoiding redundant DB lookups |

> **Tip:** Register the route in `AppShell.xaml.cs`:
> ```csharp
> Routing.RegisterRoute(nameof(ProductDetailsPage), typeof(ProductDetailsPage));
> ```
> and make sure `ProductDetailsPage` resolves `ProductDetailsViewModel` via DI or `BindingContext`.
